ATLAS cohort builder

Firstly, go to ATLAS atlas.ohdsi.org in production, where you are asked to be logged in, select “Sign in” at the top right or log in at the center of the page.

Figure 1: production environment

Then, register with a valid Google account to be able to continue on the platform.

Figure 2: production environment - Register

Once inside ATLAS, it is verified that we are in the Cohort Definitions section in the menu on the left.

Figure 3: production environment

In the filter text box at the top right, filter by the name of the cohort or a keyword that allows us to find the cohort that is required. In this study we do it with the word heart. As shown in the figure below.

Figure 4: production environment

Prevalent heart disease is selected from the filtered options for this investigation.

Figure 5: production environment

When selecting it, it appears in the Definition tab, we go to the Export tab and within it to JSON and we mark Copy to clipboard to have it in memory as shown in the following image:

Once the data is copied into memory as a template, it is passed to ATLAS DEMO atlas-demo.ohdsi.org where its own cohort is created based on in the template data that we bring.

In this platform it is not necessary to be registered, so we directly select Cohort Definitions.

Figure 7: demo environment

In this demo section we can create our own cohort by selecting New Cohort

Figure 8: demo environment

At this point we go to Export within this JSON tab and paste what was copied into the production environment to serve as a template and mark Reload.

Figure 9: demo environment

With the template already copied, we proceed to give it the name that is considered correct according to the study that is being carried out and we add the initial events and the attributes of the cohort that is being configured for its subsequent application.

Figure 10: demo environment

After configuring the previous characteristics and giving the appropriate name to the new cohort, it is saved in the disk button on the right side of the text box where the name was written.

Once the above is done, we go to the Export tab, then SQL, then Template OHDSI.SQL and copy the SQL content to take it to our RStudio and paste it into a file with .sql that will be taken into our model application.

Figure 11: demo environment

In the present study, the Target Cohort were defined as described in the previous images and the Outcome Cohort found in the DEMO environment at these respective links.

It should be noted that for the Outcome Cohort, the procedure is the same as indicated in the previous steps as in the Target Cohort.
